		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2015"></a><br><code>sle2015/paper06</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2015</a> paper:</span><br><i>Reference attribute grammar controlled graph rewriting: motivation and overview</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ChristoffBürger.html">Christoff Bürger</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2814251.2814257">10.1145/2814251.2814257</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagM">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> It is centered on semantic analyses implemented via reference attribute grammars (a static-semantics technique).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Reference attribute grammars act as a meta-language for specifying analyses over structured syntax trees/graphs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The paper discusses analysis of language descriptions/attributed specifications and how they control rewriting.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> Graph rewriting is used as a transformation mechanism controlled by the attributed specification.
</li></ul></li></ul>
